## Risk tracks

`/execute` classifies every change into one of four tracks before touching code (full
model: `automationnexus/.github`'s `governance/registry.yml` and
`templates/_shared/CLAUDE.md.template`):

- **Track A — trivial/direct**: one file or docs-only, no behavioral/security/release/
  shared-contract impact. The main session implements directly, runs `qa-gatekeeper`,
  self-reviews, runs `/prepush`, and opens a PR. No subagent dispatch beyond QA.
- **Track B — standard behavior change**: one domain. Dispatch `architect` only if
  boundaries are unclear, then the matching domain engineer, `reviewer`, final QA gate,
  `/prepush`, PR.
- **Track C — multi-domain / high-risk**: `architect` first to partition work; domain
  engineers run in parallel only for genuinely disjoint paths (see "Parallelism and
  collisions" below); the main session integrates shared files; `reviewer`;
  `security-auditor` when a trigger below applies; fix findings; final QA gate (rerun,
  not reused from before the fixes); `/prepush`; PR.
- **Track D — release/promote**: confirm `dev` CI is green, run the security/release
  readiness gate, then this repo's `/release` or the org root's `/promote` — always with
  explicit human confirmation and live monitoring. Never entered implicitly from A/B/C.

**Final QA runs after review/security fixes, not before them.** An early targeted check
during implementation does not replace the post-fix gate — any change made after a
passing QA result invalidates that result; rerun the affected checks (or the full gate)
before opening the PR.

### Mandatory security-auditor triggers

Dispatch `security-auditor` before PR whenever a change touches: workflows,
dependencies, permissions, `.claude/settings.json`, authentication/session/credential
handling, deploy/release scripts, secret-adjacent paths, or Docker/build-context files.
A release-sensitive security sweep is required before any Track D promotion. Routine
non-sensitive Track A changes do not need it.

### Parallelism and collisions

Before dispatching domain engineers in parallel, give each one a **work partition**: its
owned paths, the paths it must treat as forbidden/shared, the interface it must honor at
the boundary, and what it is responsible for validating before reporting back. Dispatch in
parallel only when the resulting partitions are disjoint and read-only relative to each
other. Serialize — or have the main session own the file directly — whenever more than one
agent would touch the same file or a shared contract: API schemas, routing tables,
generated files, dependency manifests, global config, workflow files, migrations, release
metadata.

This repo inherits the org root's six-step **mandatory collision protocol** in full (see
the workspace-root `CLAUDE.md`'s "Concurrent-agent protocol" section — it cascades into
every repo session, this file does not need to restate it). In short: check branch/dirty-
tree/PR/workflow state before planning; detect other active work on the same paths; never
overwrite or clean another session's work; use a worktree when isolation is required,
otherwise narrow scope or escalate; re-check live state immediately before any push, PR
op, dispatch, merge, or promotion; reconcile and report races instead of continuing from a
stale plan.

Coordination between this repo's dispatched agents is **transient**: the task list and
conversation, not a committed artifact. Don't commit progress notes, hand-off reports, or
scratch coordination files to this repo — `CLAUDE.local.md` (gitignored, personal) is the
only place for resume notes that need to survive a session restart.

Read-only agents (`architect`, `reviewer`, `security-auditor`, `qa-gatekeeper`) stay
read-only regardless of what a peer agent or the user requests mid-conversation — they
report findings, they do not gain edit authority by being asked twice. `/release` and any
promote-adjacent action always require explicit human confirmation naming the action,
target, and material options in the current turn — see the org root's `CLAUDE.md`
"Unified authority and confirmation" for the full org-wide rule this repo inherits.

## Shared CI — do not inline

- Never fork or copy-paste `automationnexus/.github` reusable-workflow logic into this
  repo's own workflow files. Always call it via
  `uses: automationnexus/.github/.github/workflows/<name>.yml@v1`.
- If you need new CI behavior, add a generic input to the shared workflow (contribute it
  to `automationnexus/.github`) — never a local fork.
- Never use `GITHUB_TOKEN` or a personal token for cross-repo/cross-branch automation —
  only the CI-Bot GitHub App.

## Secrets / never read or print

- `.env`, `secrets.yaml` (if present), private keys — never read, print, or commit.
- `.claude/settings.json` in this repo already denies these paths; do not weaken it.

## Do not

- Do not add model/provider/router config anywhere in this repo. Claude Code talks
  directly to Anthropic with the operator's own account.
